lois, Ewald, Helmut.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name for a tailor, literally ‘cutter’, from Middle High German <i>snīder</i>, German <i>Schneider</i>, Yiddish <i>shnayder</i>. The same term was sometimes used to denote a woodcutter. This surname is also established in many other parts of Europe, notably in France (Alsace and Lorraine), the Netherlands, Hungary, Poland, and Czechia. In Czechia, Slovakia, Croatia, and Slovenia it is also established in Slavicized forms (see 2 below). In part, <i>Schneider</i> is a Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) surname, originating from the Kočevsko region in Lower Carniola, Slovenia (see   Kocevar  ). Compare   Sneider   1,   Snider   1, and   Snyder   1.","Germanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Šnajdr</b> or <b>Šnajder</b>, and Czech <b>Šneidr</b>, <b>Šneider</b>, <b>Šnejdr</b>, and <b>Šnejder</b>, surnames of German origin (see above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Kocevar","meanings":["Slovenian (<b>Kočevar</b>): habitational name for someone from the Kočevsko region in Lower Carniola, which is named after the city of Kočevje and this one with a derivative of <i>hoja</i> ‘fir tree’, altered under the influence of the German name of the city, <i>Gottschee</i>. From the 14th century until 1941, the year of their collective resettlement in the German Reich, a large part of the region was homeland of Gottscheers, descendants of German-speaking colonists with surnames of mixed German and Slovenian origin. See also   Hocevar  , compare   Kochevar  ."]},{"name":"Schneiders","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Wolfgang.","North German: patronymic from   Schneider  ."]},{"name":"Schnier","meanings":["North German: variant of   Schneider  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from southern Yiddish <i>shnir</i> ‘cord, rope’ (see   Schnur  )."]},{"name":"Schneiderman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Ari, Meyer, Rochel, Yael, Yudel.","Americanized form of German <b>Schneidermann</b>, and a variant of the same Jewish (Ashkenazic) surname: variant of   Schneider  , with the addition of Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>man</i>, German <i>Mann</i> ‘man’. Compare   Snyderman  ."]},{"name":"Schnieder","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Bernd, Franz, Helmut.","North German: variant of   Schneider  ."]},{"name":"Schnyder","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Manfred.","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Schneider  ."]},{"name":"Sartorius","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ernst, Matthias.","German and Dutch: humanistic surname, a translation into Latin of German   Schneider  , Dutch <b>Snijder</b> (see   Snyder  ), from Latin <i>sartor</i> ‘tailor’.","French (Nord, Alsace, and Lorraine): Latinized form of   Sartor   ‘tailor’. Compare   Saddoris  ."]},{"name":"Schnettler","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Helmut, Kurt.","German (Westphalia): cognate of   Schneider  ."]},{"name":"Schneiderhan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Markus.","German: distinguishing occupational name meaning ‘Tailor John’, from   Schneider   + <i>Han</i>, a shortened form of   Johann  ."]},{"name":"Schnider","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Otto.","German: variant of   Schneider  ."]}]},{"name":"Sebastian","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Sebastianus</i>, the name of a 3rd-century saint, a Roman soldier martyred by the arrows of his fellow officers. His sufferings were a favourite subject for medieval artists. The name means ‘man from <i>Sebastē</i>’, a city in Asia Minor so called from Greek <i>sebastos</i> ‘august, venerable’, used as a translation of the Latin imperial title <i>Augustus</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sebastian Schneider was born in 1510, in Ottenhausen, Straubenhardt, Enzkreis, Baden-Württemberg, Germany as the son of Sophie von Hebel. He married Katharina Hirtler in 1543, in Ottenhausen, Neuenbürg, Württemberg, Germany. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1560, in his hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1510–1560":"1510–1560","1510–1584":"1510–1584","1515–1570":"1515–1570","–Male":"Surnud","1515–Female":"1515–Surnud","1544–Female":"1544–Surnud","1490–1554":"1490–1554","6 August 1554":"6. august 1554","1544":"1544","1510":"1510","1543":"1543","1554":"1554","1584":"1584","about 1544":"umbes 1544","1560":"1560","1570":"1570","1490":"1490","1515":"1515","Of Ottenhausen, Schwarzwaldkreis, Württemberg, Germany":"Ottenhausen, Neuenbürg, Württemberg, Saksamaa","Ottenhausen, Neuenbürg, Schwarzwaldkreis, Wuerttemberg, Germany":"Ottenhausen, Neuenbürg, Württemberg, Saksamaa","Ottenhausen, Enzkreis, Baden- Wuerttemberg, Germany":"Ottenhausen, Straubenhardt, Enzkreis, Baden-Württemberg, Saksamaa","Rauschbburg, Marburg-Biedenkopf, Hesse, Germany":"Kreis Marburg-Biedenkopf, Hessen, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1510–1560":"1510–1560","1510–1584":"1510–1584","1515–1570":"1515–1570","–Male":"Kuollut","1515–Female":"1515–Kuollut","1544–Female":"1544–Kuollut","1490–1554":"1490–1554","6 August 1554":"6. elokuuta 1554","1544":"1544","1510":"1510","1543":"1543","1554":"1554","1584":"1584","about 1544":"noin 1544","1560":"1560","1570":"1570","1490":"1490","1515":"1515","Of Ottenhausen, Schwarzwaldkreis, Württemberg, Germany":"Ottenhausen, Neuenbürg, Württemberg, Saksa","Ottenhausen, Neuenbürg, Schwarzwaldkreis, Wuerttemberg, Germany":"Ottenhausen, Neuenbürg, Württemberg, Saksa","Ottenhausen, Enzkreis, Baden- Wuerttemberg, Germany":"Ottenhausen, Straubenhardt, Enzkreis, Baden-Württemberg, Saksa","Rauschbburg, Marburg-Biedenkopf, Hesse, Germany":"Kreis Marburg-Biedenkopf, Hessen, Saksa"},"fr":{"1510–1560":"1510–1560","1510–1584":"1510–1584","1515–1570":"1515–1570","–Male":"Décédé","1515–Female":"1515–Décédée","1544–Female":"1544–Décédée","1490–1554":"1490–1554